Build troubleshooting.

Docker build has its own debugging path, mostly through build-kit's plumbing. The single most useful move is to build with plain, fully verbose progress output, which stops collapsing the log lines and shows you each step and its cache state. From there you can inspect what is sitting in the build cache, and wipe the cache to force clean rebuilds when you suspect it is lying to you.

The common build problems have recognisable signatures. Cache misses where you expected hits usually trace back to a copy whose source changed, and the plain progress output shows you exactly which step missed, often because a stale ignore file is letting irrelevant files into the context and invalidating the layer. An unknown-instruction or syntax error usually means you are missing the build-kit syntax pragma that should be the first line of the dockerfile. A failed-to-compute-cache-key error means a source path does not exist in the context, so you check the ignore file and the path itself. A slow copy step means the build context is huge, which you confirm by measuring its size and fix by trimming the ignore file. And a build that hangs while updating packages usually means the daemon's d-n-s or network is broken, which you confirm by trying to reach the internet from a throwaway container on the same host.

The through-line is that build problems are almost always one of two things, the cache behaving differently than you expected, or the context containing more, or less, than you intended. Verbose progress output plus a look at the ignore file resolves the large majority of them.
